\[y = \frac{1}{7} \left( x + \frac{3}{2} \right).\]The perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting $\left( 2, \frac{1}{2} \right)$ and $\left( \frac{1}{3}, 3 \right)$ has slope $-6,$ and passes through the midpoint $\left( \frac{7}{6}, \frac{7}{4} \right).$  Thus, its equation is
\[y = -6x + \frac{35}{4}.\]Solving, we find that the center of the circle is $\left( \frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2} \right).$

